Self-Attention is a key component of Transformer Models which helps them achieve state-of-the-art results on various NLP tasks such as language translation or summarization. The basic idea is to use attention mechanisms to attend over different parts of an input sequence (e.g., words) while taking into account all other elements simultaneously. This allows for complex interactions between distant parts of the sequence that traditional recurrent neural networks would not be able to capture efficiently.

The original Self Attention used by Vaswani et al. was quadratic in time complexity due to matrix multiplications required to calculate the weights assigned to each element in the output sequence. Subsequent research has produced several linear time alternatives known collectively as Linear Transformers including:

* Scaled Dot Product Attention proposed by Devlin et al. 2018;
* Relative Position Representation Learning proposed by Lin et al. 2020;

Linear Transformers are attractive because they do not require expensive multiplication operations like non-linear layers. However, since the weight matrices needed to compute the dot product remain unchanged from one query vector to another, this makes it challenging to model relationships between arbitrary pairs of items across long sequences. An additional limitation arises when incorporating multiple queries per encoder layer using gated multihead architectures. In these cases where both relative positional encoding and scaled dot products are computed at once, computing gradients becomes more computationally intensive than vanilla LSTM encoders. To address this, recent work by Hao Wu's group proposes a hybrid approach combining linear transforms and non-linearity only during training phases through Adaptive Computation Time Networks.<|endoftext|>

